<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-12-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-12-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="338" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d338">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Bigelow</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State,</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-12-21"><hi rend="italic">December</hi> 21, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I enclose for your information a copy of a
                            despatch of the 12th ultimo, No. 208, from Charles A. Leas, esq., the
                            United States commercial agent at <pb facs="0442" n="360" xml:id="pg_360"/> Belize, in regard to a recent proclamation of
                            Prince Maximilian affecting the British settlement in Honduras, and
                            relating also to other features of political affairs in that quarter and
                            the West Indies.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">John Bigelow,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">Chargé d’ Affaires of the United States.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>